{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ec9baefc-22bf-4cf3-aad6-8c2bade48508","content":"The template has several issues before it's ready for NuGet:\n\n**Functional bug:**\n- The `Framework` symbol is missing a `\"replaces\"` property (e.g. `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"`). Without it, the chosen framework value won't be substituted into your `.csproj`'s `<TargetFramework>` — the parameter does nothing.\n\n**Missing recommended fields:**\n- **`$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for editor validation/IntelliSense.\n- **`defaultName`** — The fallback project name when the user doesn't specify `--name` (e.g. `\"defaultName\": \"MyWebApi\"`).\n- **`preferNameDirectory`** — Should be `true` for project templates so `dotnet new` creates a subdirectory.\n\n**Missing packaging:**\n- There's no `.csproj` or `.nuspec` to build a NuGet template package. You'll need a project file with `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>` and content includes for the template files.\n- There are no actual template content files (e.g. `Program.cs`, `.csproj`) — just the config.\n\n**Verdict: Not ready.** At minimum, fix the `Framework.replaces` bug and add the template content files + a packaging project.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"10ee8951-13c5-4aa8-a68a-5b5d5cdbe132","outputTokens":326},"id":"ebb16495-51bf-4613-9dba-2fb72c7b1cfb","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:43:22.718Z","parentId":"f66b9ac3-c31a-491b-96a1-f87c6376aed7"}
